      content: "You might have noticed that updates on my blog are getting¬†a bit¬†sparse: no worries, I‚Äôm up and running as usual. Actually I‚Äôm busy as hell ‚Äì which is quite ironic, since I‚Äôd aim for a simple(r) life. But anyway: one year ago I started writing my Photoshop HTML Panels Development course, which I‚Äôve successfully published in late March 2016.\n\nI‚Äôm now back at my desk, working on a very similar project, and targeting no less than‚Ä¶ Photoshop Scripting. Yup. First things first, here‚Äôs the way for you to both receive news on the project status as months go by ‚Äì the release date is Q2/2017, so don‚Äôt hold your breath ‚Äì and an exclusive, substantial discount coupon few days before the course will be publicly available. The mailing list will have ultra-low traffic, don‚Äôt expect to receive more than two or three emails during these months.\n\n\n\nPlease subscribe, it‚Äôs also useful for me to assess what the interest upon this course is like; besides, it‚Äôll save you some good money.\n\nTell me more!\n\nI‚Äôve been working¬†for something less than¬†a couple of months, so it‚Äôs really too early to describe a course that is in its early development phase. I can tell you that what has driven me undergoing¬†such a crazy task is the lack of existing resources, describing a linear learning path to get to Scripting enlightenment. Forums are full of helpful people, there are blogposts, articles, references ‚Äì yet, the available documentation (in the term‚Äôs broadest sense possible) is scattered to say the least. Which, alas, is very Adobe-ish.\n\nThe Scripting community itself is composed of very few, very talented and skilled developers; while the average coder is either self-taught (and that‚Äôs a tough business ‚Äì been there myself), or with a patchy knowledge. Web and JS developers entering the Photoshop¬†world may have hard time too ‚Äì ExtendScript has its own quirks and peculiarities indeed. What about other CC apps? I‚Äôve always had the impression that the InDesign Scripting community ‚Äì on average ‚Äì is better equipped; and please note that I‚Äôm not interested in the developers‚Äô elite, but the community‚Äôs at large. It might be that InDesign has a better, cleaner ExtendScript implementation (yes, it‚Äôs different); I‚Äôve had a look at their official documentation, and I‚Äôm biased to think that, as always, education plays a role.\n\nThis course aims to be my own take on providing one, among the many possible others, learning path. It‚Äôs a pretty darn minefield, though. The topic‚Äôs so vast that it‚Äôs impossible for me to cover it all ‚Äì so most of my sweating goes into finding the right way, to cover the right topics, in the right order (being ‚Äúright‚Äù what makes sense to me). The course target is impossibly crazy¬†both newcomers and ¬†experienced developers. I‚Äôve started softly, emphasizing not only the language, but the programmer‚Äôs mindset too.\n\nAnd yes, I will devote an entire fat chapter on¬†ActionManager, aka Scripting Voodoo. I‚Äôm eager to get there, but it‚Äôll take time :) I can‚Äôt provide any sample content yet, except few¬†screenshots: compared to the HTML Panels course, this one looks better to my eyes ‚Äì I‚Äôve refined my style, also thanks to customers‚Äô feedback.\n\n\n\t\n\tRandom pages from the first draft\n\n\nI plan to blog about this course three-four times in total:¬†the early announcement (this very post), when I‚Äôll be midway through it, and finally to announce the actual release date, with a final reminder. You won‚Äôt hear me talking too much about this :) A dedicated website will follow, very much like the HTML Panels course, and bundled videotutorials are planned as well. To save your fingers a little scrolling work, here is the newsletter form again ‚Äì please subscribe if you‚Äôre interested. Thank you! üôèüèª\n\n\n",
